 Crop-Wise Drought Sensitivity Mapping in Idaho Using the Vegetation Drought Response Index (VegDRI), 2024
 
1. What Is VegDRI? 
The Vegetation Drought Response Index (VegDRI) is a weekly drought-monitoring product for the United States.
It helps identify how vegetation is responding to drought stress, not just climate dryness.
VegDRI was developed jointly by:
â€¢	USGS EROS Center
â€¢	National Drought Mitigation Center (NDMC), University of Nebraska
â€¢	High Plains Regional Climate Center (HPRCC)
VegDRI combines:
 Satellite-based Vegetation Condition Metrics
â€¢	Derived from MODIS (Terra) at 1 km resolution
â€¢	Uses two important NDVI-based indicators:
o	PASG â€” Percent Annual Seasonal Greenness
o	SOSA â€” Start of Season Anomaly
These capture how green the vegetation should be, and how abnormal the growing season start is.
 Climate-Based Drought Indicators
â€¢	Palmer Drought Severity Index (PDSI)
â€¢	Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI)
These detect dryness and water deficit.
 Biophysical & Environmental Data
â€¢	Land use / land cover
â€¢	Soil available water capacity
â€¢	Elevation
â€¢	Irrigation status
â€¢	Ecological region
Environmental stresses (fire, pests, flooding, hail, land-use change) can also modify vegetation condition.
Why VegDRI Is Useful for Agriculture
Unlike basic drought indices, VegDRI tells us exactly how crops are reacting to drought conditions.
For Idaho croplands (e.g., alfalfa, potatoes, barley, wheat), VegDRI helps quantify:
â€¢	Which crops show higher drought stress
â€¢	Where crop-specific vulnerability exists
â€¢	Spatial differences within the same crop type
â€¢	Crop-wise sensitivity patterns within a single year (2024)
 
