CODE LINK:https://code.earthengine.google.com/d096fbda16de94f552d03255fad59829
1. Idaho Boundary
var idaho = ee.FeatureCollection('TIGER/2018/States')
  .filter(ee.Filter.eq('NAME', 'Idaho'));
This isolates Idaho for all VegDRI calculations.
Everything is clipped or masked to this boundary.
 
2. Load VegDRI Weekly Images for 2024
var vegdri_raw = ee.ImageCollection('projects/climate-engine-pro/assets/ce-veg-dri')
  .filterBounds(idaho)
  .filterDate('2024-01-01', '2025-01-01');
VegDRI is produced weekly, so 2024 contains ~52 images.
Using all weeks captures season-long drought behavior.
 
Scale VegDRI Values
function scaleVeg(img){
  return img.addBands(
    img.select("vegdri")
      .subtract(128)
      .divide(16)
      .rename("vegdri_scale")
  );
}
var veg2024 = vegdri_raw.map(scaleVeg);
VegDRI stores values as encoded integers.
The decoding function converts to a continuous âˆ’5 to +5 drought scale.
 
3. VegDRI Color Palette
var vegPaletteSimple = [
  "#720206","#cb3121","#e36b09","#fee301",
  "#ffffff","#88f9c7","#53c285","#2b8032"
];

This palette moves from extreme drought â†’ extreme moisture,
mirroring VegDRIâ€™s conceptual scale.
 
4. Cropland Data Layer (CDL)
var cdl = ee.ImageCollection("USDA/NASS/CDL")
  .filterBounds(idaho)
  .sort("system:time_start", false)
  .first();

Each pixel in CDL represents a specific crop type.
This allows VegDRI to be extracted per crop.
Your Idaho crop list:
â€¢	Corn
â€¢	Barley
â€¢	Spring Wheat
â€¢	Winter Wheat
â€¢	Alfalfa
â€¢	Potatoes
â€¢	Sugarbeets
 
5. Annual VegDRI Composite
var veg_annual = veg2024
  .select("vegdri_scale")
  .mean();

Taking the mean of all VegDRI weeks gives a season-integrated drought view,
which smooths short-term weather noise and highlights overall crop stress patterns.
 
6. Crop-Specific VegDRI Maps
function addCropAnnual(crop){
  var mask = cdl.eq(crop.value).selfMask();
  var layer = veg_annual.updateMask(mask);
  Map.addLayer(layer, {min:-5, max:5, palette: vegPaletteSimple}, crop.name);
}
crops.forEach(addCropAnnual);

Different crops react to water stress differently.
This step creates one VegDRI layer per crop, so we can compare sensitivity:
â€¢	Cereals (barley, wheat) may show early-season stress
â€¢	Potatoes are highly drought sensitive
â€¢	Alfalfa can be resilient but still affected in dry irrigation cycles
 
7. Crop-Wise Drought Statistics
reduceRegion({ reducer: mean + stdDev })
This computes average VegDRI + standard deviation for each crop.

â€¢	Mean VegDRI shows general drought intensity
â€¢	StdDev tells how variable the stress was across growing areas
(useful for crops grown in both irrigated and semi-arid zones)
 
8. Bar Chart (Mean VegDRI per Crop)
ui.Chart.feature.byFeature(stats_fc, 'crop', ['mean'])
Theory:
This provides a quick crop-ranking of drought stress,
useful for:
â€¢	drought impact assessment
â€¢	crop sensitivity comparison
â€¢	irrigation management insights
 
